node.text:
The other day I ran into this rock star up in the mountains - @ashimashiraishi was trying a heinous sport route in cloudy and snowy conditions. Unsurprisingly, it was too wet to send, but I was pretty impressed that she was trying. And the day after a strong World Cup lead performance as well!⁣⁣
⁣
For anyone who’s listened to any of @climbinggold this season you know that a lot of what we explored was the spectrum of athleticism to adventure in climbing. Some folks worry that as climbing gets more athletic (hello, Olympics!) that climbers forget the adventurous side. I personally have always argued that a higher degree of athleticism just allows for bigger adventures. ⁣⁣
Either way, super nice to run into an elite competition climber, from New York City no less, up high in the mountains.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Alex Honnold on July 17, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text: This is a photo of the south face of the Aiguille du Midi - one of the most accessible walls in all the Alps it would seem since it’s right below the gondola station from town. I took the pic just because I’ve never seen so many climbing parties converged on one piece of rock. People talk about crowding in Yosemite, but look at the starts of these routes! Amazing!! Like ants on a piece of cheese. I was so impressed that I stopped and took off my gloves to take a pic, like a real tourist… the climbing above Chamonix is such an interesting world.

node.text:
One of the projects that the Honnold Foundation (@honnoldfoundation) is supporting this year is installing a rooftop solar array on a tuition-free all-girls school in Liberia called Hilltop Schools (@hilltopschoolsliberia). When the 15 kW solar array is complete it will power the entire campus, which provides a solid education, meals, and medical care, among other services. ⁣
⁣
It's very similar to a project that we supported last year with Association MAIA (@maia_impact) - a school for indigenous girls in Guatemala. It makes total sense to use renewable energy to lower their utility costs (and provide more reliable power) and allow them to focus more resources on their specific missions of education. I love win-win solutions, and it's a great pleasure to be able to help these organizations do their important work. There are links in my bio to the HF website for anyone interested in more info on either organization, and for further information on our 2021 partners.⁣
 ⁣

There’s a new feature on the Honnold Foundation website (@honnoldfoundation) called the Sustainability Tick List - it’s inspired by my own long journey to lower my environmental impact however I can. It’s meant as a helpful list for anyone looking for personal actions they can take. It will certainly evolve over time (much like my reading list on the HF site) so feel free to add suggestions or ideas. Link in bio to learn more. ⁣

node.text:
It's been a big year for podcasting for me: I’m excited to be hosting “Planet Visionaries,” a new podcast with @rolex about the scientists and innovators helping to safeguard Earth for future generations. It's a very different feel than the climbing stories that I've been sharing, but it's been a real pleasure to chat with some incredibly smart folks who are doing meaningful environmental work. ⁣
⁣
Check out the trailer (link in my bio), and make sure to subscribe wherever you get your podcasts! ⁣
⁣

Found this little guy while trotting down from the crag the other day - pretty exciting for me because I’ve never seen a mountain lion in the wild. And also kind of scary. But not too scary to watch him (her??) for a while and try to sneak some pics…
This is the side of Vegas that folks don’t think about when they’re checking into their hotel on the Strip…
